THOUGHT: The program crashes with an AddressSanitizer report indicating a stack-buffer-overflow in the `crc8` function. The overflow occurs at `buf[i]` when `i` reaches `len`, which is the size of the buffer (`sizeof(buf)`). The loop condition `i <= len` is incorrect — it should be `i < len` because `buf` has `len` elements indexed from `0` to `len-1`. Accessing `buf[len]` reads beyond the buffer, causing the overflow. The stack frame shows `buf` is 7 bytes (offset 32 to 39), and the access at offset 39 is the first byte past the buffer. This is a classic off-by-one error.

ROOT CAUSE: In `program.c` at line 12, the loop condition `i <= len` in the `crc8` function causes an out-of-bounds read of `buf[i]` when `i == len`, which is one past the end of the `buf` array. Since `buf` has `len` elements (7), accessing `buf[7]` reads memory beyond the allocated stack buffer, triggering a stack-buffer-overflow.

LOCAL FIX: Change the loop condition from `i <= len` to `i < len` in the `crc8` function to ensure the loop only accesses valid indices of the buffer.

```c
for (size_t i = 0; i < len; i++) {
    crc ^= buf[i];
    for (int b = 0; b < 8; b++) {
        crc = (crc & 0x80) ? (uint8_t)((crc << 1) ^ 0x07) : (uint8_t)(crc << 1);
    }
}
```

GLOBAL FIX: Replace the raw array and size parameter with a bounded view type (e.g., `struct buffer_view`) that enforces bounds at compile time. This prevents off-by-one errors by ensuring the function only operates on valid, bounded data. For example, define a `buffer_view` struct with a pointer and length, and use it in `crc8`'s signature. This enforces correct usage and eliminates the possibility of passing an invalid length or accessing out-of-bounds memory.

